subSubSection.paragraph:
The neck is creamy, and dorsalstripes and head forks are reddish to blackish, thin, and sharply marked. The pale color of the head, neck, and upper back of the Javan Slow Loris often cause confusion with the Bengal Slow Loris (N. 
bengalensis
), especially in museum collections, and indeed, these species are genetic sister taxa. The diamond pattern that forms between the eyes is a defining character of the Javan Slow Loris. Ears are small with tufts. The second incisor is always absent. Two forms occur throughout the year inJava—one with a short coat that is sometimes red, but often dark brown, and one with a very long coat that is always dark brown or very black. The latter was originally named N. ornatus. It remains to be seen if these are different taxa. Two of the same morph have not yet been seen at the same locality in the wild.
